<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Upholds Law Banning Campaign Donations From Unions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Upholds Law Banning Campaign Donations From Unions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1606205094 Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network in 
Portuguese 1000 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1606205094 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salete Sobreira] </F>
  [Text] The Federal Supreme Court [STF] has upheld a legal 
provision that prohibits both political parties and candidates 
from accepting donations for electoral campaigning from trade 
unions and similar organizations. 
  Paragraph 6 of Article 45 of the law prohibits candidates 
and 
parties from receiving, whether directly or indirectly, any 
donation in money or in any other form that could be translated 
into money -- including any kind of advertisement -- from unions 
or similar organizations. 
  By a vote of six to three, the STF thus turned down a 
petition filed by the Workers Party to have the above law 
declared unconstitutional. Justice Sepulveda Pertence, who 
heard the case, voted with the minority. He believes that 
unlike unions, associations could make donations because they do 
not collect mandatory dues and contributions from their members. 
  Justice Neri da Silveira, who voted down the PT petition, 
said that the ban also affects associations, in order to prevent 
powerful economic organizations from committing excesses. The 
STF has ruled that the law will stand, but that it will be 
incumbent upon the Superior Electoral Court to rule on the case 
of PT presidential candidate Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, who is 
facing charges for having used a sound truck from the 
metalworkers union of the ABC region [Sao Paulo industrial belt] 
in his electoral campaign. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

