<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujimori Returns, Says Cuba Poses No Threat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fujimori Returns, Says Cuba Poses No Threat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1606162094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1342 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1606162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 16 Jun (EFE) -- Peruvian President Alberto 
Fujimori said today in Lima that Cuba does not pose a threat to 
the Americas, and that an embargo against Cuba or against any 
other country in the world is therefore unjustified. 
  Fujimori made this statement after his return from Colombia, 
where he attended the Fourth Ibero-American Summit in Cartagena 
on 14 and 15 June. 
  Fujimori, who visited China and Japan before his visit to 
Colombia, said that what Latin America is currently spending on 
weapons should be invested in development. 
  Commenting on Peruvian domestic policy and former President 
Alan Garcia, who has been in asylum in Colombia since June 1992, 
Fujimori said: "I cannot accept an agreement with or even 
negotiate with a person who destroyed the country." 
  Recently there has been conjecture about a possible 
rapprochement between the government and the American Popular 
Revolutionary Alliance (APRA), the party led by Alan Garcia, who 
ruled Peru from 1985 to 1990. 

</TEXT>

