<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   University Students End Strike, Resume Classes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    University Students End Strike, Resume Classes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1606232594 Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 10 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PY1606232594 </F>
<F P=104>  Montevideo EL PAIS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Most of the University of the Republic's nearly 
60,000 students will return to classes on 13 June. But they will 
no longer occupy buildings or demonstrate for bigger budgets. 
They will come to study, if they want. 
  On 9 June, the four university associations decided to lift 
the strike that halted classes and research at the university. 
The strike lasted 45 days but teachers and employees continued 
receiving their salaries. 
  The strike started on 25 April. It was staged in demand of a 
20 percent salary increase [for faculty members] that, according 
to students, was the cost of living increase last year and was 
what the government promised to give the faculty in April 1993. 
  What students finally got was a 6 percent increase through a 
law approved by Congress that interpreted a previous decision 
and that, according to the University Inter-Association, "merely 
corrected the illegal discrimination against the university." 
The students also collected 436,400 signatures in support of a 
plebiscite proposing a constitutional amendment to assure bigger 
education budgets in general. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

