<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Find 42 Gasoline Bombs in School </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Find 42 Gasoline Bombs in School </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1706022094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2042 GMT 16 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1706022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Caracas, 16 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- The Venezuelan police 
found 42 gasoline bombs at a high school in the capital today. 
Meanwhile, student protests against the government continue. 
  Orlando Hernandez, chief of the Metropolitan Police (PM), 
told the press his men had also found enough fuel and containers 
to make an additional 50 Molotov cocktails. The materials were 
found at Andres Eloy Blanco High School. 
  Student demonstrations worsened in the last few hours, in 
protest of the repression against student activities, the high 
cost of living, the plans to increase fares for urban 
transportation, and the government's poor handling of the 
banking crisis. 
  Hundreds of depositors of the eight banks in which the 
government intervened yesterday gathered outside the head 
offices of these institutions in an attempt to pressure the 
government into allowing them to withdraw their money. 
  The government will administrate the funds of the eight 
intervened banks. Depositors will be allowed to have access to 
only a portion of their money. 
  A group of students from a high school in the western 
section 
of Caracas hurled rocks and gasoline bombs at riot police, who 
responded with tear gas to disperse the demonstrators. Two 
policemen were injured in the clashes and taken to nearby 
hospitals. 
  In other cities around the country, such as Maracaibo, 
Barquisimeto, and Valencia, protests continued for a third 
consecutive day. In light of this, the National Guard has moved 
in. 
  Local news media have reported 100 peasants were arrested in 
the town of Turen, 400 km from Caracas, after staging 
demonstrations to protest high prices and looting several stores. 
  Defense Minister Rafael Montero has accused Lieutenant 
Colonel Hugo Chavez Frias (who led the February 1992 coup 
attempt) of being one of the instigators of the recent wave of 
protests the country has experienced. 

</TEXT>

