<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Courts Deny U.S. Extradition Request </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Courts Deny U.S. Extradition Request </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606203994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1847 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1606203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 16 Jun (ACAN-EFE) -- Costa Rican courts 
today denied the U.S. request to extradite Hubert Matos Araluce, 
son of Cuban anti-Castro leader Hubert Matos, who is wanted by 
U.S. authorities for fraud. 
  The Fourth Constitutional Chamber's decision, which was 
disclosed today, confirmed that Matos Araluce has been a Costa 
Rican citizen since 24 March, according to a National 
Immigration Council agreement. 
  The extradition request, the higher court emphasized, was 
made after Costa Rican citizenship was granted to Matos Araluce, 
who is currently entitled to the protection of Costa Rican laws. 
The higher court indicated in its decision that the 
Constitution stipulates that no Costa Rican citizen, either by 
birth or naturalization, can be deported or extradited from the 
country. 
  The decision also required the state to compensate Matos 
Araluce for damages. In the extradition request, submitted by 
the U.S. Embassy in San Jose, Matos Araluce is accused of 
repeated fraud in Florida. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34300 </DOCNO>
