<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guatemala's De Leon on Caribbean Basin Initiative </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guatemala's De Leon on Caribbean Basin Initiative </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1906195494 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
1900 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1906195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] While in Cartagena de Indias, where he attended the 
Fourth Ibero-American Summit, Guatemalan President Ramiro de 
Leon Carpio discussed the Central American governments' request 
to U.S. President Bill Clinton that the U.S. Government 
implement the benefits approved for Central America in the 
framework of the Caribbean Basin Initiative [CBI]. 
  [Begin De Leon recording] We addressed a note to him 
expressing our concern regarding the agreements reached during 
GATT's Uruguay Round on 15 April, whereby the U.S. Government 
would apply a tariff on its beef imports. In our note, we 
pointed out that this decision would have a negative effect on 
economic reactivation and the consolidation of stability in our 
countries. For this reason, we emphasized in our note that the 
current concept of economic development and the United States' 
new foreign policy in Central America emphasize trade more than 
they do aid. We told President Clinton that, to be consistent 
with this policy, CBI benefits should continue to cover all of 
our beef exports without volume limitations, because, as we all 
know, cattle raising in Latin America plays a very important 
role in economic reactivation, job creation, and, of course, 
exports. We expect a favorable answer to this request. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

