<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paraguay's Wasmosy Rejects Cuban Blockade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paraguay's Wasmosy Rejects Cuban Blockade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1606225294 Asuncion ULTIMA HORA in Spanish 16 Jun 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> PY1606225294 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ULTIMA HORA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by unidentified "special" reporters from Cartagena </F>
de Indias, Colombia] 
  [Excerpts] At the closing of the Fourth Ibero-American 
summit of heads of state and government that was held in this 
city, President Juan Carlos Wasmosy on 15 June expressed his 
rejection of the trade embargo on Cuba. Nonetheless, he urged 
Cuban President Fidel Castro to effect a democratic opening in 
his country. [passage omitted] 
  Wasmosy referred to the situation confronting the Cuban 
nation: "We are against blockades, but by the same token we 
request that there be a greater democratic opening in Cuba. 
Resolutions taken in that country will thereby have more 
legitimacy." 
  Another issue discussed by the heads of state and government 
was the "right to life." But no consensus was reached on it in 
order to draft a joint summit declaration. 
  The subject was discussed on 15 June by Argentine President 
Carlos Saul Menem, who in a plenary summit session moved that a 
unified pronouncement condemning abortion be made. This motion 
was supported by Wasmosy. 
  Our head of state said: "We protect the right to life. We 
believe that there is life from the moment an ovum is 
fertilized. Therefore, pursuant to our religious beliefs and 
laws, we deem that abortion is a crime." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

