<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Details Charges Against Self-Employed Workers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Committee Details Charges Against Self-Employed Workers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1706172094 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1706172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "First Thing" program] </F>
  [Text] Inspectors from nine Havana administrative councils 
have fined over 300 self-employed workers for violations and 
irregularities in exercising this type of work. Provinicial 
labor committee figures indicate that 26,388 inspections had 
been conducted by the end of May in the 133 self-employment 
categories approved by the provincial administrative councils. 
Of the 555 fines, over 300 were issued against people who do 
unauthorized work and 60 people who render services but were not 
registered with the municipality. Another group was issued 
fines for using middlemen or selling products in areas 
prohibited by the city's regulations. The labor committee also 
revoked the licenses of over 350 repeat offenders and has 
confiscated merchandise, mainly snacks and agricultural 
products, from approximately 60 people. 
  Manuel Fernandez, director of labor and social security in 
Havana, said the fines total over 450,000 pesos and affirmed 
that strict controls will be maintained. Fernandez also said 
that over 40,000 people are registered for self-employment work 
in Havana. 

</TEXT>

