<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Support for `Second Generation Economic Reforms' Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Support for `Second Generation Economic Reforms' Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1706012494 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1706012494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary] </F>
  [Text] Cuba's presence at the Fourth Ibero-American Summit 
in Cartagena de Indias was closely linked with its interest in 
adopting specific actions in favor of regional integration. That 
is why it supported previous presidential summits and the one 
that recently concluded in Colombia. Everything that sponsors 
trade -- investments, exchanges, technical aid, and scientific 
and technical cooperation in this hemisphere -- has been firmly 
supported by this blockaded island. In fact, the Cuban position 
goes so far as to support the so-called second generation 
economic reforms proposed by the United States for this region, 
provided the summit unilaterally organized for December in Miami 
does not become a forum to set guidelines for Latin America and 
to isolate Cuba. 
  Making progress within the integration plans is still part 
of 
the Cuban position, even when results achieved in this respect 
at three previous summits have somehow failed to fulfill the 
hopes for an effective, specific consensus. Even though Latin 
American countries have participated in the integrationist 
efforts exerted for many years, they admit they have yet to 
eliminate the obstacles that must preclude an integration in the 
economic, trade, and investment sectors despite a more favorable 
international situation. This is proved by the underhanded 
economic pressure frequently exerted by the United States on 
nations in this geographic area. 
  The presidents' reflections on the economic, trade, and 
financial blockade against Cuba were not directly expressed in 
their speeches to the fourth summit's plenary session, nor were 
they included in the lengthy text of the final declaration. 
Paradoxically, the most important international organization, 
the UN General Assembly, approved resolutions that condemn the 
blockade that the United States maintains against our country, 
yet the summit of statesmen and rulers in this hemisphere 
briefly alludes to the unjustifiable measure without even 
calling it by its name. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34339 </DOCNO>
