<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1806000694 </F>
<F P=103> PY1806000694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Chile monitored through 16 
June. 
  The Italian multinational company Parmalat S.P.A. bought 51 
percent of the shares of the Chilean company Soprocar Inc., 
which makes and sells Copalca dairy products. On 25 May, 
Parmalat President Calisto Tanzi and Soprocar President Hernan 
Bozzo signed the agreement through which the Italian company 
officially entered the Chilean dairy products market under the 
name of Parmalat Chile. Soprocar general manager Gonzalo Martino 
reported that the initial investment totals $20 million. 
(Santiago LA TERCERA DE LA HORA in Spanish 26 May 94 Economic 
Section p 4) 
  The National Statistics Institute, INE, reported that the 
unemployment rate was 5.3 percent in the February-April period, 
an increase of 0.1 percentage point compared with the previous 
quarter, and 0.9 percentage point compared with the same period 
last year. This is the highest rate since September 1992. The 
number of employed people was 4,962,230, an increase of 2.6 
percent compared with 1993. This means that 126,490 jobs were 
created. The INE also reported that the unemployment rate 
dropped in five of the 13 regions during this period. (Santiago 
LA TERCERA DE LA HORA in Spanish 2 Jun 94 p 3) 
  Mexican and Chilean aeronautics authorities signed an 
agreement through which Chilean airlines will transport 
passengers from Mexico to San Jose de Costa Rica and Guatemala 
on their routes from Mexico to Chile. Air traffic between Chile 
and Mexico has increased considerably in the past few months. A 
total of 11,714 passengers and 551 metric tons of cargo were 
transported in the first four months of the year, an increase of 
5 percent and 65 percent, respectively, compared with the same 
period last year. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 1618 GMT 10 Jun 94) 
  The Chilean companies Copec, Sipetrol, and Enap, which made 
up the Latin American Oil Company, Clapsa, and the U.S. company 
Oryx Energy won the bid to prospect for oil in Ecuador for four 
years. They signed a risk contract in which they will invest $45 
million. The Chilean companies share the contract with 32.5 
percent and the U.S. company with 50 percent. The area to be 
prospected totals 2,000 square kilometers. (Madrid EFE in 
Spanish 1608 GMT 10 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

