<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turnout Highest in History </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turnout Highest in History </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2006042394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0130 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2006042394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "TV Today" Newscast] </F>
  [Text] The abstention rate dropped by 55 percent and voter 
turnout increased by more than 1 million compared to the first 
round of elections on 29 May. 
  [Begin unidentified reporter recording] Abstention was 
defeated very early in Santa Fe de Bogota, especially at the 
largest polling station, Corferias [exhibition center], where 
thousands of people lined up at the 226 voting tables there. A 
high percentage of young people decided to break their silence 
and vote in this round. However, many voters were turned away 
because they were not registered on the electoral lists. The 
voting took place in an atmosphere of relative normalcy without 
the presence of entertainers [animadores] -- as was permitted in 
the elections four years ago -- in keeping with the new 
electoral laws banning partying. 
  In the presence of authorities, electoral information tables 
were set up outside Corferias with propaganda of the Liberal 
candidate, while the public force closely watched the voting 
inside the Santa Fe de Bogota exhibition center. 
  There were no incidents, and the abstention that marked the 
29 May elections suffered a relative defeat today. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

