<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Several Bombs Detonate in Medellin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Several Bombs Detonate in Medellin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1706192394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 1730 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1706192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Medellin has suffered several bomb attacks in the 
past few hours. According to authorities, the bombs were of 
medium power. 
  Eleven 7-kg bombs were detonated against banking and 
financial institutions, while two others were defused by the 
police. The attacks started at 2300 local and the explosions 
occurred simultaneously in central Medellin and the 
northeastern, northwestern, and southern areas of the city. 
  [Begin recording] [General Luis Ernesto Gilibert, head of 
the 
Metropolitan Police] Since last night, we have been preparing 
for new terrorist attacks. 
  [Reporter] Who are the perpetrators of these attacks? 
  [Gen Gilibert] Subversives, who attempt to hamper the 
electoral process. [end recording] 
  The explosions, which caused damage amounting to more than 
100 million pesos, injured a young girl. Police have posted a 
reward of 10 million pesos for information on the identities of 
those responsible for the terrorist actions. The police believe 
members of an ELN [National Liberation Army] city cell are 
responsible for these incidents. The ELN is also blamed for an 
attack on a police patrol on Tuesday. Personnel of security 
agencies are on a first- level alert to guarantee public order 
in the Antioquia Department capital city. 
  [Paris AFP at 1447 GMT on 17 June transmits a 229-word 
report 
stating that 17 bombs were set off Thursday night in Medellin, 
each with an estimated 5-kg weight] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

