<H3> <TI>   Pastrana, Samper Make Campaign Statements 17 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pastrana, Samper Make Campaign Statements 17 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1806035694 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 1730 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1806035694 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Midday Television Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Barely 43 hours before the election that will decide 
who will be the new president of Colombia, voter preference is 
more divided now than in previous elections. Recent polls 
indicate a virtual tie between the two candidates. The election 
results on 19 June will surely be a photo finish. This is why 
Ernesto Samper Pizano and Andres Pastrana Arango will begin a 
bona fide Colombian tour in order to secure the votes that will 
take them into Narino Presidential Palace. 
  Andres Pastrana will visit Armenia, Pereira, Medellin, 
Moteria, Cartagena, Barranquilla, Santa Marta, Valledupar, 
Cucuta, and Bucaramanga this weekend. Meanwhile, Ernesto Samper 
Pizano will visit Popayan, Pasto, Neiva, and a half dozen other 
cities in the southwest. The two candidates are asking 
Colombians to defeat abstention on 19 June. Before beginning 
their tours, the two candidates expressed their confidence in 
winning: 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Why should 
Colombians vote for you? 
  [Pastrana] For change. The country realized on 29 May the 
country can change. People saw change was, in fact, possible; 
that is why we are telling the people that if one extra person 
votes for Andres along with the 2.5 million Colombians who did 
the last time, we will have consolidated change in Colombia. 
  [Reporter] Why should Colombians vote for you? 
  [Samper] Because I believe I have the necessary experience 
and knowledge to administrate the country. I have an excellent 
running mate, Humberto de la Calle. We represent the new 
Colombia. We represent those who do not want to be 
discriminated against and want better living conditions. I am 
ready to make the social turn Colombia needs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

