<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Caldera on Wave of Rumors, Economic Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caldera on Wave of Rumors, Economic Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1806000994 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1806000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vicente Briceno; from the "Union Radio News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] President Rafael Caldera has said that the most 
prosperous industry in Venezuela is spreading rumors. He added 
that this, however, is countered by reality because our 
democratic system is firm and stable. Caldera made this 
statement during a joint news conference with Portuguese Prime 
Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva at the Yellow House. Caldera 
recalled that recently rumors persistently circulated in the 
country about his presumed death, which had to stop when all 
Venezuelans confirmed that he was totally active. 
  [Begin Caldera recording] I am convinced that the democratic 
system in my country is a firm and stable reality, and will be 
maintained despite all the rumors unleashed by those who are 
interested in creating situations of violence and instability, 
taking advantage of the grave circumstances of an economic 
crisis. We are all aware of the seriousness of this crisis and 
we know that we must make great efforts to overcome it. [end 
recording] 
  Caldera attributed the fall of the bolivar to the wave of 
rumors, which in turn has increased inflation. 
  [Begin Caldera recording] We are fighting against inflation, 
but rumors are the main cause for its increase. We are facing a 
situation of shortages and price fluctuations in which 
speculators take advantage of any factor or announcement that 
the inflation rate is up to increase prices to unacceptable 
levels. We will handle this problem with courage and 
determination. [end recording] 
  President Caldera said that despite the crisis in the 
financial system, the fact that foreign investors are still 
interested in investing in our country is proof that Venezuela 
will be able to overcome this crisis and reactivate its economy. 
  Meanwhile, Portuguese Prime Minister Cavaco Silva said that 
his country is willing to assist Venezuela under the current 
circumstances and to strengthen commercial ties between both 
countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

