<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, URNG Reach Accord on Resettlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government, URNG Reach Accord on Resettlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1806000894 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2238 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1806000894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New York City, 17 Jun (DPA) -- The Guatemalan 
Government and the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity 
(URNG) reached an agreement today in Oslo on the resettlement of 
people uprooted by the internal strife that shook the country 
for 30 years, the United Nations reported today in New York 
City. The agreement will not enter into force until the 
government and the URNG sign a final peace agreement at the end 
of this year. The preparatory work for this accord will begin 
in the next 60 days, it was announced. 
  Once the resettlement concludes, the sides will begin to 
discuss the topic of the "identity and rights of Indian 
peoples," which is the next step in the negotiations. This new 
pact, accompanied by the one signed already on human rights, 
consolidates the possibility of bringing to an end the longest 
continuing conflict in Latin America, the United Nations 
indicated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

