<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canceling Argentine Visit Unrelated To Support for Salinas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canceling Argentine Visit Unrelated To Support for Salinas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1806034694 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2149 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1806034694 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 17 Jun (AFP-NA) -- The Brazilian Foreign 
Ministry on 17 June expressed its malaise over the stance taken 
by Argentina during the Ibero-American Summit of heads of state 
and government held in Cartagena de Indias (Colombia) last week 
concerning its endorsement of Mexican President Carlos Salinas 
de Gortari as a candidate for the GATT presidency. 
  Notwithstanding this, a Brazilian diplomatic spokesman told 
AFP NEWS AGENCY that the suspension of Argentine Economy 
Minister Domingo Cavallo's visit to Brasilia -- scheduled for 
the end of June -- until July was a "coincidence" and had 
nothing to do with the other issue, as had been hinted at by the 
local press on 17 June. 
  The Itamaraty (seat of the Brazilian Foreign Ministry) 
spokesman reported that having officially announced the 
candidacy of Finance Minister Rubens Ricupero for GATT's 
presidency on 7 June, the Brazilian Government informed its 
Latin American counterparts. 
  On that occasion, Argentina and Mexico -- without making any 
type of commitments -- allegedly had been in favor of Ricupero's 
candidacy to replace Irishman Peter Sutherland. 
  This is why it was considered in "poor taste" that another 
candidate was proposed and supported in the absence of the 
Brazilian delegation (when President Itamar Franco left the 
summit due to the unexpected death of his nephew and private 
secretary, Ariosto Franco). 
  The same source said, nonetheless, that this will neither 
affect Brazil's good relations with Argentina nor the Common 
Market of the South [Mercosur] integration process, nor 
negotiations on the establishment of a South American Free Trade 
Zone sponsored by Brazil. 
  The suspension of Cavallo's trip to Brazil was made at the 
request of the Brazilian Finance Ministry, which at the time 
originally scheduled for his visit -- the end of June -- will be 
putting the final touches on the implementation of the new 
currency at par with the dollar -- the real -- scheduled for 1 
July. 
  Cavallo's visit surely will take place at the end of July 
after the Mercosur summit in Buenos Aires that will be attended 
by Argentine President Carlos Menem, Brazilian President Itamar 
Franco, Paraguayan President Juan Carlos Wasmosy, and Uruguayan 
President Luis Alberto Lacalle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

