<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indians Protest Agrarian Reform Bill Amendment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indians Protest Agrarian Reform Bill Amendment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1706204294 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 13 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1706204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Quito -- President Sixto Duran-Ballen has signed 
into law a controversial amendment to the Agricultural Reform 
Law, despite the Indian communities' threats to demonstrate 
until the amendment is repealed. The bill proposed is meant to 
modify agrarian reform to increase the country's agricultural 
production. The Indian and peasant communities, however, think 
the new measure is harmful because it offsets the agrarian 
reform's increased benefits and empowers the government to 
confiscate land presently owned by Indians and hand it over to 
wealthy landlords. 
  Before the bill was approved, Indian organizations closed 
roads and organized marches to the Congress. Now that the bill 
has been signed into law, the Confederation of Indian 
Nationalities of Ecuador [CONAIE] threatens to intensify the 
protests until the law is repealed. Traditionally, the Indians' 
protests have been marked by the closure of highways and 
confrontations with the police but without excessive violence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

