<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havana Film Festival Director Defects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havana Film Festival Director Defects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1906234194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2232 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1906234194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 19 Jun (EFE) -- Jose Horta, director of 
the Havana Film Festival, informed EFE today of his decision not 
to return to Cuba after being mistreated by the police of his 
country. Horta, who is also international relations director of 
the Cuban Institute of Arts and Motion Picture Industry (ICAIC), 
told EFE that the police arrested him on 18 June as he was 
leaving the Havana airport on his way to Mexico. He said he was 
taken off the plane twice while the police thoroughly searched 
his luggage. He said the Cuban authorities later refused to 
return his passport. 
  The reason for his trip to Mexico was to promote the New 
Latin American Film Festival, which is held in Havana every 
December. "This situation has been humiliating. I never 
thought I would ever abandon Cuba, but this abuse is 
intolerable. I do not know if this is part of the prevailing 
wave of repression in the country, but I will not tolerate it 
any longer," he said. 
  Horta, who has been director of the film festival for four 
years and has participated in its organization for the past 16 
years, said he has not yet decided whether he will request 
political asylum in Mexico or if he will travel to the United 
States. 
  Roberto Casin, former PRENSA LATINA director in Mexico, 
defected in May 1991 while in Mexico and later traveled to 
Miami, the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

