<H3> <TI>   Holds Talks With Lage, Alarcon </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Holds Talks With Lage, Alarcon </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106004194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2301 GMT 20 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2106004194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 20 Jun (PL) -- Cuban Vice President Carlos 
Lage today received Christine Stewart, Canadian minister of 
state for Latin America, who also met with other prominent Cuban 
officials and held talks termed positive. 
  Ricardo Alarcon, Ernesto Melendez, and Jose Luis Rodriguez, 
foreign investment, cooperation, and finance ministers 
respectively, also received Stewart during the first day of her 
two-day working visit to Cuba, which has a full agenda. An 
official from the Canadian Embassy in Havana said these were 
constructive and "very smooth" talks. 
  As she arrived in the Cuban capital last night, the 
official, 
also in charge of African affairs in Prime Minister Jean 
Chretien's liberal administration, pointed out one the 
objectives of her trip was to broaden bilateral ties. She also 
underscored that common programs could stem from these 
conversations. 
  Meanwhile, Foreign Affairs Minister Andre Ouellet said the 
Canadian Government today ended the 16-year suspension of 
official economic aid to Cuba, convinced that "now is the time 
to turn the page" on Cuba. 
  This aid was canceled on 1978 due to the Cuban military aid 
offered to Angola in view of the South African aggression. This 
decision, however, did not hinder bilateral relations, 
especially commercial and tourist relations, which thrived 
without difficulties. 
  According to Ottawa government sources, Canada will grant 
Cuba over $1 million worth of foodstuffs, mainly for children, 
between 1994 and 1995. Stewart is expected to make a public 
announcement regarding this aid tomorrow morning in Havana. 

</TEXT>

