<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gold Mine Inaugurated in Western Province </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gold Mine Inaugurated in Western Province </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2006015594 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1602 GMT 15 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2006015594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pinar del Rio, Cuba, 15 Jun (PL) -- A gold mine, 
with a production capability of approximately 500 kg a year, was 
inaugurated in this western province with an initial yield of 
100 grams of this precious mineral. 
  The Canadian-built facilities are located in the Castellanos 
bed and use a system of zinc precipitation, which is widely used 
in the international gold industry, to extract the mineral. 
  According to mining authorities, this mine opens new 
possibilities for Cuba to diversify its economy. In addition to 
Castellanos, Cuba has gold deposits in the Isle of Youth 
(Delita), in the central province of Villa Clara (El Descanso), 
and in the eastern provinces of Camaguey (Jobabo) and Holguin 
(Aguas Claras). 
  The most promising of those gold deposits is the one located 
in Delita. Experts have concluded, however, that this is where 
gold extractions will be more difficult because the mineral is 
accompanied by large amounts of arsenic, which is definitely an 
undesirable element. 
  Cuba is divided into 37 areas for geological prospects. More 
than 20 contracts have been signed with foreign investors, 
particularly from Canada, for the exploration of solid minerals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

