<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Paralyzes 3 Districts, Protests Electoral Fraud </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Paralyzes 3 Districts, Protests Electoral Fraud </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106005994 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2322 GMT 20 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2106005994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 20 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- The Committee for 
the Defense of Democracy in the Dominican Republic today 
paralyzed three Valverde districts to protest the fraud 
committed in the 16 May general elections, local police sources 
reported. 
  The protest, which was organized by opposition political 
parties, affected Esperanza, Mao, and Laguna Salada, where 
stores closed and urban and intra-urban transportation 
decreased, a Dominican radio station reported. 
  Some 20 people were arrested and are under investigation for 
throwing tacks on the streets, burning tires, and detonating 
explosive devices, police reports stated. 
  Committee members were linked to the Santo Domingo 
Agreement, 
which established a coalition made up of opposition parties led 
by Jose Francisco Pena Gomez of the Dominican Revolutionary 
Party (PRD) and the Democratic Union (UD). 
  Pena Gomez, who was favored to win the elections in the 
Dominican Republic, today reiterated his charges of electoral 
fraud and presented the Central Electoral Board [JCE] with "new 
evidence" that holds that organization responsible for the 
irregularities. 
  JCE initial results show that President Joaquin Balaguer, 
candidate for the Social Christian Reformist Party (PRSC), is 
leading by a minimum margin, but electoral authorities have not 
yet proclaimed his victory. 
  JCE President Manuel Garcia Lizardo reaffirmed that the 
board 
will not proclaim a winner yet based on the official results of 
the elections because every one of the reported irregularities 
is being investigated. 
  Meanwhile, Balaguer and Dante Caputo, UN envoy to Haiti, 
discussed the Haitian crisis behind closed doors. Caputo, who 
arrived in the morning, refused to give details on his meeting 
with Balaguer, but said they discussed international initiatives 
on the Haitian case. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

