<F P=101> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Haitian Vessel Intercepted; Crew Interrogated </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Haitian Vessel Intercepted; Crew Interrogated </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106004794 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2304 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2106004794 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 20 Jun (EFE) -- Today, a U.S. Coast 
Guard vessel intercepted a Haitian vessel transporting food and 
textiles from Miami to the Haitian northern coast, sources from 
the Dominican Republic's Defense Ministry told EFE. 
  The boat, named "Roxanna," with registration number 
AK212-212, was intercepted in front of the Dominican Port of 
Manzanillo, close to the Haitian border, in the Dominican 
Republic's northwestern region. The vessel was delivered to the 
Dominican Navy at the Puerto Plata dock in the Dominican 
Atlantic Coast, where two other Haitian vessels are being held. 
  The ship was transporting wheat flour, vegetable oil, rice, 
other food products, and some textiles. The crew members -- the 
exact number was not specified -- are being interrogated in 
Puerto Plata by Dominican authorities, who have strengthened the 
embargo -- on the economy, oil, and weapons -- declared in a UN 
resolution to force the Haitian military leaders to surrender 
power and to permit the return of deposed President 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

