<H3> <TI>   Jonassaint Presides at Ceremony Marking New Flag Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jonassaint Presides at Ceremony Marking New Flag Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2006155694 Paris AFP in Spanish 1436 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2006155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 20 Jun (AFP) -- This morning, 
Haiti's provisional President Emile Jonassaint, who has not been 
acknowledged as such by the international community, personally 
hoisted his country's blue and red flag in front of the National 
Palace as numerous Haitian and foreign journalists watched. 
  Earlier, an official communique had announced that "from now 
on, the national flag will remain at the top of the flagpole 
until further notice, and it will be saluted every morning. The 
daily ceremony of lowering the flag has been abolished." The 
purpose of this measure is to strengthen the "flag's symbolism" 
to contribute to the safeguarding of "national independence." 
  Bernard Sansaricq, president of one of the Senate's 
opposition blocs (not acknowledged by the international 
community), and Army Chief General Raoul Cedras, along with the 
Haitian military high command, were at Jonassaint's side. 

</TEXT>

