Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1806040294 </F>
<F P=103> PA1806040294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
21 August. 
  Tens of thousands of National Autonomous University of 
Mexico 
students and faculty members cheered Party of the Democratic 
Revolution [PRD] presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas 
during a 6 June campus rally. Cardenas warned students that 
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has "set up the mechanisms 
to commit electoral fraud" and called for a "deluge of 
democratic votes" to overcome the stumbling blocks, traps, and 
fraud. Cardenas said the three essential conditions for 
transition toward democracy are: 1) support for an active and 
involved civilian society; 2) following Cardenas' victory, the 
beginning of a transition toward democracy; and 3) a complete 
revision of constitutional bases and an open debate on a new 
constitution. (Monterrey EL NORTE (Foreign Edition) in Spanish 
7 Jun 94 p 1A) 
  According to a survey published today in VOZ Y VOTO 
magazine, 
the Institutional Revolutionary Party [PRI] has lost 13 percent 
of its voter support in three years and now registers only 48 
percent voter support. The PRI received 61.47 percent of the 
votes in the 1991 Federal District election. The poll was 
conducted between 13 and 17 May following the public debate 
between presidential candidates Zedillo, Fernandez de Cevallos, 
and Cardenas. Results show the PRI would get 48 percent of the 
votes; the National Action Party [PAN], 26 percent; the PRD, 9 
percent; the Labor Party [PT], 1.48 percent; the Mexican Green 
Ecologist Party [PVEM], 0.84 percent; the Popular Socialist 
Party [PPS], 0.71 percent; the Cardenist Front for National 
Reconstruction Party [PFCRN], 0.32 percent; and the Authentic 
Party of the Mexican Revolution [PARM] and the National 
Opposition Union [UNO], 0.26 percent each. Only 2 percent of 
those polled indicated they would not vote, and 11 percent 
declined to respond. Polled on personal versus party appeal, 
the results varied slightly: PRI presidential candidate Ernesto 
Zedillo would get 49 percent of the votes; PAN candidate Diego 
Fernandez de Cevallos, 26 percent; PRD candidate Cuauhtemoc 
Cardenas, 11 percent; PFCRN candidate Rafael Aguilar Talamantes 
and PT candidate Cecilia Soto, 2 percent each; and UNO candidate 
Pablo Emilio Madero, 1 percent. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 1816 GMT 
9 Jun 94) 
  PRI candidate Ernesto Zedillo visited a Mexico City railroad 
station and received an enthusiastic welcome from workers, whom 
he promised he would give an unprecedented boost to rail 
transportation and improve living conditions for railroad 
workers. Zedillo said the only acceptable government is that 
which is based on valid elections, adding that he was sure "the 
people would disregard any call to attack institutional rule and 
the social tranquillity and unity of Mexicans." Zedillo later 
met with small and medium business representatives, who listened 
with interest to the PRI economic platform. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 14 Jun 94) 
  Diego Fernandez de Cevallos, PAN presidential candidate, 
said 
that although the failure to reach a peace agreement in Chiapas 
is disturbing, it is important that the cease-fire be maintained 
and that the two parties remain willing to continue talks. 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 14 Jun 
94) 
  Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, PRD presidential candidate, 
said in Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua State, that the failure of the 
government and of the armed groups in Chiapas to reach a peace 
agreement should not affect the 21 August elections, nor should 
it create an atmosphere of instability in the country. Cardenas 
later met with businessmen in Ciudad Juarez and told them it was 
necessary to broaden the jurisdiction of state and national 
human rights groups by extending "their purview to political and 
labor rights to give greater protection to the rights of all 
citizens according to the Constitution and the laws." (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 14 Jun 94) 
  PARM presidential candidate Alvaro Perez Trevino said 
during the second day of a campaign tour through Zacatecas that 
a 70-percent voter turnout would be a genuine representation of 
Mexican citizens in the presidential elections. Trevino was to 
meet with the university's law school students, but the meeting 
was canceled due to poor attendance. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 14 Jun 94) 
  Referring to the Zapatist National Liberation Army's (EZLN) 
rejection of the Chiapas peace proposal in Veracruz, PT 
presidential candidate Cecilia Soto said that "a more precarious 
peace now exists." She proposed the creation of a secretariat 
for women to protect women in the labor and legal fields. Soto 
met with PT party leaders and supporters in Veracruz. (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 14 Jun 94) 
  Jorge Gonzalez Torres, PVEM presidential candidate, arrived 
in Oaxaca on 13 June to begin a 10-day tour of Indian 
communities in the Mizteca and coastal areas and on the Isthmus 
of Tehuantepec. Speaking of his commitment to the 
underprivileged classes in Mexico, Gonzales Torres said the 
issue is not just "drug trafficking but also includes poverty 
and the abandonment of peasants and the poor." (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 14 Jun 94) 
  Asked about the recent events in Chiapas, PAN presidential 
candidate Diego Fernandez de Cevallos said the least the 
presidential candidates can do is show prudence and not assume 
opportunistic positions. He said he was not surprised by the 
EZLN's rejection of the proposal because it was obvious when the 
document was released that it would be rejected by the guerrilla 
group. The government's reply to the EZLN was not clear, 
Fernandez de Cevallos said. He recalled that Subcommander 
Marcos recently said that EZLN members felt deceived, "but 
fortunately they said they will not renew the violence." 
Fernandez de Cevallos said the EZLN insists on further 
negotiations and wants a new, prudent, and honest effort. He 
added that the candidates must assume "very delicate" positions. 
Fernandez de Cevallos said candidates could and should express 
their opinions on the issue, but warned that any proposal urging 
the EZLN or the government to take specific action could easily 
be viewed as opportunistic. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 
14 Jun 94 p 5) 
  Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, National Democratic Alliance (ADN) 
presidential candidate, told those who favor the postponement or 
cancellation of the elections that he will demand that the 
elections be held on 21 August as scheduled. During a visit to 
the Autonomous University of Ciudad Juarez (UACJ), Cardenas also 
asked the government and the EZLN to renew negotiations and 
establish conditions for a lasting peace as soon as possible. 
  Cardenas added that the ADN would work within the law and 
also demand that the law be respected and that the votes be 
counted fairly. During a morning news conference, he said he 
did not believe the EZLN announcement rejecting the government 
offer would affect the upcoming elections. He said the 
government must seek solutions to local, state, and national 
issues raised by the EZLN, such as how the government can 
guarantee clean elections and improve health and education. 
Cardenas said PRI candidate Zedillo's question to Peace 
Commissioner Manuel Luis Camacho -- Why has the peace effort 
failed? -- was directed at the wrong person. "The question 
should be asked of President Salinas de Gortari," Cardenas said, 
adding that the recent car bombing incident in Guadalajara "is 
evidence of the social disintegration caused by the current 
government." (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 14 Jun 94 p 6) 

</TEXT>

