<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Leon: Summit Strengthened Central American Bloc </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    De Leon: Summit Strengthened Central American Bloc </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2006204394 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1206 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2006204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 17 Jun (ACAN-EFE) -- On Thursday, 
Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon Carpio stressed that the 
strengthening of the Central American bloc was the most 
significant achievement of this week's Fourth Ibero-American 
Summit in Colombia. 
  When he returned to Guatemala, De Leon told the press that 
the six countries agreed that in the future there will be no 
bilateral negotiations, except in very special cases, because 
from now on everything will be done as a single bloc. In 
discussing specific achievements, he mentioned the 
capitalization of the Central American Bank of Economic 
Integration (BCIE) with the support of Argentina (which will 
contribute $70 million), while Colombia and Venezuela are 
awaiting final approval of contributions of $70 million and $122 
million, respectively. 
  The Central American presidents also met with the leaders of 
Chile, Spain, and Mexico, but they had to cancel their meeting 
with Brazilian counterpart Itamar Franco, who had to leave 
early. Mexico is already an extra-regional partner which has 
contributed $122 million to the region. 
  De Leon said the Central American bloc was looking for $700 
million to strengthen "our financial arm" and to carry out the 
region's Alliance for Sustainable Development project. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

