Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Financial Bodies Pledge $150 Million in Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Financial Bodies Pledge $150 Million in Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2006224994 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1346 GMT 17 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2006224994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, 17 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- The international 
community and the world financial organizations today committed 
themselves to delivering $150 million to Nicaragua during the 
1994-95 period to consolidate the peace process and promote 
economic development. 
  The Advisory Group for Nicaragua said the two $75-million 
financial aid installments for 1994 and 1995 will be used to 
boost the economic development of that Central American nation. 
  At the conclusion of a two-day, closed-door meeting, 
Edilberto Segura, World Bank director for Mexico, Central 
America, and Panama, remarked on Nicaragua's democratic progress 
in 1993. 
  The donor countries asked the Nicaraguan Government to focus 
on fighting poverty, reducing the foreign debt, modernizing the 
public sector, and settling property disputes. 
  Mark Schneider, deputy director of the U.S. Agency for 
International Development's Latin American and Caribbean 
division, said: "The poorest of the poor must be the main 
beneficiaries of this financial aid." 
  The World Bank said the main challenge for Latin America "is 
to promote and sustain balanced growth while maintaining 
economic stability in view of possible reductions in 
international financial aid." 
  Nicaraguan Presidency Minister Antonio Lacayo, who headed 
the 
Nicaraguan delegation, said "the only war we can wage now is a 
war on poverty," adding that "the armed conflict, 
totalitarianism, and backwardness must be left behind." 
  The government official asked the World Bank and the IMF to 
expedite their disbursements and increase their co-financing. 
Lacayo emphasized that it is necessary for them to provide $60 
million annually to increase funds to invest in rural 
production, especially small-scale production. 
  The Advisory Group meeting took place at the Paris World 
Bank 
quarters and was attended by delegates from Germany, Austria, 
Canada, Denmark, Finland, France, the Netherlands, Italy, Japan, 
Luxembourg, and Mexico. Representatives from Sweden, 
Switzerland, Spain, the United States, and Venezuela were also 
present, as were World Bank and IMF officials. 
  The Pan-American Health Organization, UNICEF, the OECD, and 
the International Agricultural Development Fund also attended 
the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34512 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat119_j_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-119 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Haitians To Receive `Special Treatment' After 26 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Haitians To Receive `Special Treatment' After 26 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106034094 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 18 
Jun 94 p A1 </F>

<F P=103> PA2106034094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] Immigration Department Director Antonio Dominguez 
said yesterday "400 Haitians who are in the country on tourist 
visas" will receive special treatment "when commercial flights" 
to that Caribbean island "are suspended." 
  Dominguez said Haitians who are in the national territory 
after 26 June--the date on which the suspension of commercial 
flights to Haiti begins--"will not be classified as political 
refugees" because they entered the country as tourists. 
  Dominguez asserted that among other mechanisms the 
Immigration Directorate may implement regarding the Haitians, 
"it is scheduling a charter flight to return the Haitians to 
Haiti" if the crisis in that former French colony is not 
resolved. 
  The Immigration Department director revealed that "Haitians 
wishing to enter Panama must have an authorized visa, which has 
been suspended for citizens of that Caribbean nation." 
  According to Dominguez, "visas are only being given to 
Haitians who reside in the United States to come to Panama for 
three days to purchase merchandise." 
  Finally, Immigration Director Antonio Dominguez remarked 
"this situation will affect Panamanian companies which do 
business with Haitians." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

