<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ex-Shining Path Members Enter Country Illegally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ex-Shining Path Members Enter Country Illegally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2106131394 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 20 
Jun 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PY2106131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santiago del Estero (DYN) -- Eleven former members 
of Peru's Shining Path organization reportedly entered Argentina 
illegally and are traveling to Buenos Aires to file for 
residency as refugees. 
  The group's spokesman, Jorge Diaz Reategui, said that after 
defecting from the Maoist guerrilla organization, the 11 wended 
their way south with the assistance of international agencies 
including the United Nations. 
  "First we went to Ecuador and later Brazil and Colombia," 
said Diaz Reategui, "but those countries did not agree to accept 
us as refugees." 
  Diaz Reategui said he was a fighter with the group, known as 
Sendero Luminoso in Spanish, but had only participated in three 
conflicts. 
  The spokesman said the UN was supporting the former senderos 
in Argentina. He added that he had been detained by police in 
Tucuman for 10 days. 

</TEXT>

