<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mercosur Vice Economy Ministers' Meeting Ends </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mercosur Vice Economy Ministers' Meeting Ends </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2006174194 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2314 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2006174194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 17 Jun (EFE) -- According to remarks 
by Argentine Foreign Trade Secretary Carlos Kesman, great 
strides were made at the meeting of vice economy ministers of 
Common Market of the South [Mercosur] member countries that 
ended on 17 June. 
  Kesman did not make any concrete announcements about the 
progress made at the meeting. He just stated that it was a 
"working meeting" and therefore nobody expected any changes to 
what had been agreed to by Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, and 
Uruguay. 
  The analysis of all the pending points on the common 
external 
tariff (AEC) was among the most salient issue discussed in the 
nearly eight-hour-long meeting at the Economy Ministry building 
in Buenos Aires. 
  Kesman also highlighted the controversy between Argentina 
and 
Brazil over capital goods in general and computer software and 
hardware in particular. He nonetheless denied reports about an 
alleged "flexibility" evinced by Brazilian authorities. 
  The four countries' representatives also analyzed aspects 
pertaining to the establishment of free trade zones and the 
reconciliation of tax policies. 
  The Argentine delegation was headed by Carlos Sanchez, the 
trade and investment secretary, and Jorge Campbell, the under 
secretary for commercial integration, who were accompanied by 
Kesman and Alejandro Mayoral, the under secretary for sectorial 
programming and integration. 
  Also attending the meeting were [Economic Policy Secretary] 
Winston Fritch from Brazil -- Finance Minister Rubens Ricupero's 
right-hand man, Economy and Finance Under Secretary Juan Ignacio 
Garcia Peluffo from Uruguay, and Integration Vice Minister Ruben 
Fadlala from Paraguay. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

