<H3> <TI>   Chiapas Governor Awaits EZLN Reply </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chiapas Governor Awaits EZLN Reply </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106202694 Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 20 Jun 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> PA2106202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City UNOMASUNO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Betzy Villarreal Rodas] </F>
  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez, Chiapas, 19 Jun -- Today, Governor 
Javier Lopez Moreno, federal and state coordinator of peace 
efforts in Chiapas, said he is awaiting a reply from the 
Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN] to begin exchanging 
work plans and commitments that will lead to the signing of a 
regional peace agreement. 
  Lopez Moreno, however, pointed out that he is not currently 
seeking a dialogue with the EZLN in the buffer zones. He added 
that he will meet today with Bishop Samuel Ruiz Garcia, when the 
prelate returns from a trip. 
  The state governor delivered a message to the people of 
Mexico and Chiapas: "We are not experiencing the worst of 
conditions, and we are making progress." I trust the EZLN's 
conditions will be appropriate for the holding of elections, and 
even the electoral campaign. 
  He admitted he has good relations with all political 
organizations in the state. He also said he was in a position 
to resolve the agenda proposed by the State Council of the 
Indian and Peasant Organizations as well as to resolve the 
concerns expressed by the small landholders, particularly the 
cattle ranchers. 
  He advised that there are problems in some municipalities in 
the state, such as land seizures, the blocking of highways, and 
unrest in the zones of conflict. Nevertheless, he said, the 
situation is under control. 

</TEXT>

