<H3> <TI>   IFE To Monitor Media Campaign Coverage </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IFE To Monitor Media Campaign Coverage </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2206010494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0104 GMT 19 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2206010494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 18 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- The Mexican Federal 
Electoral Institute (IFE) General Council announced today that 
it will monitor the media to see if reports on the presidential 
candidates' campaigns are fair and objective. During a regular 
session this Saturday, IFE members unanimously agreed to order 
the institution's Radio Broadcasts Commission to file a report 
on their findings by the end of the month at the latest. 
  The Commission is to report to the Council every 15 days 
until the political campaigns conclude on the handling of 
information reported by the media. 
  Over 40 million Mexicans will go to the polls during 21 
August's federal elections to choose a president, 500 deputies, 
128 senators, and 66 Assembly members. The IFE General Council 
plan includes a recommendation to the media, mainly radio and 
television stations, to balance information on the political 
campaigns of the various parties. It also asks the electronic 
media to respect, in their radio and television newscasts, the 
right of Mexicans to be informed about the campaign activities 
of the nine presidential candidates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

