<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Decries U.S. Visa Application Fee </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Decries U.S. Visa Application Fee </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106202494 Paris AFP in Spanish 1746 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2106202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tegucigalpa, 21 Jun (AFP) -- Honduran Foreign 
Minister Ernesto Paz Aguilar today described as "unfair, 
lamentable, and deplorable" the $20 fee for each visa 
application charged by the U.S. Consulate in Tegucigalpa. 
  "It is unfair so much money is charged for a simple, 
administrative form," the Honduran minister said, reacting to a 
decision the U.S. Government announced on 20 June. This 
decision will be applied in all Central American countries. 
  Fernando Sanchez, the U.S. consul in Tegucigalpa, has said 
the charge is to prevent people who do not even have $20 from 
approaching the U.S. Consulate to request a visa, because their 
intention is none other than to migrate to the United States. 
  "I believe this is an unfair decision. I have said the only 
way to prevent large flows of Caribbean and Central American 
immigrants to the United States and the developed countries is 
by consolidating freer, stronger, and more competitive economies 
in our countries," Paz Aguilar said. 
  According to Sanchez' estimates, approximately 50,000 
Hondurans go to the consulate every year to request visas, of 
which approximately 30,000 are granted, meaning the consulate 
would be receiving $1 million if the current flow of 
applications continues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

