<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106221694 </F>
<F P=103> PA2106221694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Honduran economic developments monitored through 21 
June. 
  The Honduran private banking sector has disclosed that 
non-traditional Honduran exports increased by 22 percent in 
1993. According to the Tegucigalpa-based Banco Atlantida, income 
from non-traditional sales on the international market amounted 
to $226 million. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1957 GMT 13 Jun 94) 
  The Central Bank Board of Directors has decided to increase 
its cash reserve by six points. This will begin on 16 June and 
is to be done gradually, increasing one point every 15 days 
until it reaches 40 percent on 30 September. This is a measure 
to prevent the sliding of the lempira with regard to the dollar 
and to put a stop to the spiraling inflation. (San Pedro Sula 
TIEMPO in Spanish 15 Jun 94 p 3) 
  A banking source told ACAN-EFE that the fever to save 
dollars 
in Honduras has reduced deposits in the local currency by 1.3 
percent. According to this source, the country's monetary system 
is experiencing a "strong expansion of deposits in dollars," and 
has surpassed expectations in less than a year. (Panama City 
ACAN in Spanish 1442 GMT 18 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

